Text.Value: Chef Roveer still hears squeaking. Why do you not kill rats? Rats too tough?
Killing's killing, don't say you love your work if you ain't sticking by it. Real Bhaalspawn would kill them rats.
Leave.
The rats are unimportant - your name is on a list of murder targets. You need to hide.
Speak? To the filthy vermin who are ruining my stock? I think not.

EditorData.NodeContext: more put out as opposed to outraged

Text.Value: True adventuring soul, you are. No battle too small!
Chef Roveer has been staying most vigilant since your warning, yes. Only murders in this kitchen will be of the rat-kind.
You did? Very clever. Good job, yes. Here, you take this.
Ey! We got rats in t'cellar. We also got cats, but cats are useless, so how about you kill the rats?

EditorData.logicalname: Greeting Killed Rats Before Meeting Reevor

Text.Value: Leave.
Do not worry - Chef Roveer's eyes will be kept peeled for murdering types.
Eh, I - uh, I mean if you could get to the rats, that'd be great. Nothing better to practise your skills on than a few rats.

EditorData.NodeContext: nervous, trying to be jovial at the end

Text.Value: I don't eat rats. Rude dwarves, on the other hand...
You dare ask this of me, the literal child of Bhaal, god of murder?
Ey, you already got paid, no more work here. Plenty o' rats elsewhere in the city, go kill those.
It would be my pleasure.
Leave.
I need to warn you, chef - your name is on a murderer's target list.
Adventurers have to get their start somehow. Ye haven't got the spirit of a hero in ye if you think you're above killing a few rats.
Leave.
Damn rats. Eh, you!
I thought I asked you to clean the rats out of this cellar yesterday, already. Go on - rip 'em apart with them chompers if you have to!
I thought I asked you to clean the rats out of this cellar yesterday, already. Hop to it! Get in there!
Insult Chef Roveer's reward if you want, but someday you will look back and say, 'Killing rats - that was a mighty task!'
They're not animals. They're vermin. They're a source of diseases and infections and they're ruining my stock!
I was just down there. Those rats are the size of ponies.
Probably. Lot of rats in this world. Been having problems with 'em in cellars for the whole twenty years of my career.
No, I need them rats taking care of!
I would never kill an innocent animal!
Haven't I done this before?
I'm an adventurer, not an exterminator.
You need to forget killing rats - someone's out to kill you. You're on a murder target list.
Rats, murderers... Always knew the chef gig wasn't going to be easy.
You're mistaken. We've never met.
And do not worry - Chef Roveer's eyes will be kept most peeled for murderous knaves.
Really? I could've sworn you were an adventurer. You look like an adventurer. And you talk like an adventurer. So you must be an adventurer!
Oh, go on. Nothing better to practise your skills on than a few rats.
I can see in your eyes - you want to warn me of killers again. No! The only murder I want to hear of is rat murder. Begone!
You kill the rats, yes? I heard commotion in the cellar. Good, perfect - here, you take this.

EditorData.logicalname: REEVOR HASMET AND RATS KILLED, GIVING REWARD

Text.Value: Good news, chef! I already killed the rats.
Actually, I'm here to warn you. You're on this list of murder targets - you need to hide.
Just kidding! The rats are dead, but you can keep your paltry reward.
What! Giant rats! No, I do not believe it, giant rats is silly.
Why don't you simply speak to them?
Here's the deal - I'll keep a look out for murderers, you murder the rats.

Synopsis: Dialog with Chef Reevor  III  at Elfsong Tavern. Related con Revoor,the dwarf that gives players the first quest in the original Baldur's Gate. He has a problem with rats at the cellar.
